Comment: 1) The final image was not visible in my browser for some reason.  2) I'm a little bit concerned about drawing conclusions about these classes of visualizations from the particular examples.  There may be peculiarities of the specific examples that are not necessary features of the whole class.  For example, when the time bar just shows values of 0 and 250 ms, that reduces the information available.
The questions on the previous page had no image of ERPs associated with it - an image did not load.
One of the question did not have any image at all.
Occasionally the page would load slowly and I would see the filename of the figure prior to it loading. You might consider obscuring the ERP component in the figure name to prevent bias/priming.
Over all images, there was the same title. Some images did not load, many of them needed me to reload the site over and over until they were displayed.
for the last three questions, no ERP display was available.
please, let us know the outcome of the study. Thanks!

I think with the multiplot form (all time series on a layout) there is an issue of scaling, so only large effects can be seen. The color coded channels options is definitely the prettiest, but if there are many channels it becomes very difficult to understand.
without info about cond1 and cond2, the questions 'which component?' are hard to answer.  good luck with your investigations

Difference waves are absolutely useless without providing information on the single conditions. Not properly labeling x- and y-axes makes the figures completey useless. If I were to see any of these figures in a paper I had to review, I'd suggest major changes.

I like the topography-plus-superimposed-ERPs plot, but I don't like that it's limited to displaying differences between conditions (since it would be difficult to superimpose conditions in the already superimposed ERP plots).

Knowing which type of stimuli are being used aids a lot in the interpretation of plots. The average responses across the max response electrode (max ROI of electrodes) imo tends to be the best visualisation of ERPs.

Great idea! It was difficult for me to know whether with component you mean identify _any_ component (there were always visual components) or N170/P300.    I really like topographies. Maybe something like this: https://github.com/behinger/eegvis/ might be helpful. I.e. do not show just few topographies at the peaks of the components, but many topographies throughout time.    Thanks for making nice visualizations available in MNE!

Here are some of the tings that motivated my responses:  - in general, color-coding (as in the red/blue square plots showing negativities/positivities over time per electrode) loses information relative to seeing the traces over time  - in general, difference waves lose information relative to seeing individual condition traces  - the rainbow colored electrode locations are interesting but I imagine it takes some training until you know the color-location mapping and it starts to (maybe?) become useful
My favorite representation is the last one: the colorful time-domain plot with the topography plots for the key peaks.
